.TH GET_SOCKDELAYS 8 "2026-07-13" "Linux 6.6" "System Administration"
.SH NAME
get_sockdelays \- display per-socket network delay statistics
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B get_sockdelays
.RB [ \-p
.IR pid ]
.RB [ \-i
.IR inode ]
.RB [ \-r ]
.RB [ \-n ]
.RB [ \-h ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B get_sockdelays
queries the kernel "net_delayacct" generic netlink family (provided
by the
.B CONFIG_NET_DELAYACCT
option) to retrieve per-socket network delay statistics.
.PP
It is the socket-level counterpart of
.BR getdelays (8),
which queries the
.B taskstats
family for per-task delay accounting.
.PP
For each TCP/UDP socket held by a target process, the kernel returns:
.IP \(bu 2
socket type (TCP/UDP) and address family (IPv4/IPv6)
.IP \(bu 2
local and remote IP addresses and ports
.IP \(bu 2
owning task comm and PID
.IP \(bu 2
socket inode number
.IP \(bu 2
cumulative receive and send latencies (in nanoseconds) and the
corresponding packet counts
.PP
The average latency is computed by the tool as
.I total_ns / count
and is displayed in microseconds by default (or nanoseconds with
.BR \-n ).
When the packet count is zero, the average is shown as
.IR N/A .
.SH OPTIONS
Exactly one of
.BR \-p , " \-i , " " \-r "
must be specified.
.TP
.BR \-p " " \fIpid\fR
Display statistics for every TCP/UDP socket held by the process with
PID
.IR pid .
Each socket is printed on its own line.
.TP
.BR \-i " " \fIinode\fR
Display statistics only for the socket whose inode number matches
.IR inode .
.TP
.BR \-r
Reset all per-socket delay statistics in the kernel to zero. Requires
.B CAP_NET_ADMIN
(equivalently, root).
.TP
.BR \-n
Print latencies in nanoseconds (default: microseconds, two decimal
places).
.TP
.BR \-h
Print a usage message and exit.
.SH OUTPUT
The tool prints a header line followed by one line per socket. Fields
are (in order):
.RS
.TS
lb l.
TYPE	protocol: TCP or UDP
FAMILY	address family: INET (IPv4) or INET6 (IPv6)
LADDR	local IP address
LPORT	local port (host byte order)
RADDR	remote IP address
RPORT	remote port (host byte order)
COMM	owning task comm
PID	owning task PID
INODE	socket inode number
AVG_RX	average receive latency (us, or ns with \-n; N/A if count==0)
AVG_TX	average send latency (us, or ns with \-n; N/A if count==0)
.TE
.RE
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
Show all sockets of PID 1234:
.B get_sockdelays -p 1234
.TP
Show the socket with inode 8765432:
.B get_sockdelays -i 8765432
.TP
Reset all statistics:
.B get_sockdelays -r
.TP
Display latencies in nanoseconds:
.B get_sockdelays -p 1234 -n
.SH FILES
.TP
.I /proc/net/genetlink
Lists registered generic netlink families; the
.I net_delayacct
family appears here when the kernel option is enabled.
.TP
.I /proc/<pid>/fd
Used to discover socket inode numbers for use with
.BR \-i .
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR getdelays (8),
.BR ss (8),
.BR iperf3 (1),
.BR netperf (1),
.BR delay-accounting (7),
.BR taskstats (7)
.SH AVAILABILITY
The
.B get_sockdelays
source is shipped under
.I tools/net/get_sockdelays/
in the project tree. The corresponding kernel framework lives in
.I net/core/net-delayacct.c
and is enabled by the
.B CONFIG_NET_DELAYACCT
Kconfig option.
